    ("Data assimilation in NWP:", ["uses only surface thermometer readings", "combines observations from multiple sources (satellites, radiosondes, aircraft, buoys, radar) into optimal initial conditions for model runs", "ignores satellite data entirely", "only occurs once a year"], 1, "Merging imperfect observations with model background."),
    ("Model resolution affects forecast quality because:", ["coarser models are always better", "finer grid spacing resolves smaller-scale weather features like individual thunderstorms, improving detail and accuracy for local forecasts", "resolution has no effect on accuracy", "only time resolution matters"], 1, "Higher resolution = more detail but more computational cost."),
    ("Analog forecasting is a technique that:", ["is the primary method used today", "finds historically similar weather patterns and uses their outcomes as guidance, useful when models struggle with rare events", "has completely replaced NWP models", "only works for temperature forecasts"], 1, "Supplemental to NWP, especially for extreme events."),
    ("Medium-range weather forecasts (3–10 days) have improved primarily because:", ["we stopped using computers for forecasting", "better observations, data assimilation, improved model physics, and more powerful computers have extended useful forecast skill to about 7–10 days", "weather has become more predictable", "only one improvement was needed"], 1, "Multiple advances compound."),
    ("MOS (Model Output Statistics) correct model forecasts by:", ["replacing all model data with observations", "applying statistical relationships between model output and observed weather to reduce systematic biases in model predictions for specific locations", "ignoring the numerical model entirely", "only adjusting temperature forecasts"], 1, "Post-processing to improve model output for local conditions."),
